</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="114" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="114">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="114">
<taxonomicName authority="Kaszab, 1982" authorityName="Kaszab" authorityYear="1982" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Wattius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Wattius cucullatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cucullatus">Wattius cucullatus</taxonomicName>
can be separated from all other known members of the genus based on the following character combination: Frontoclypeal suture strongly incised, frons shallowly depressed anterior to eyes; pronotal horn strongly produced, apex weakly bifurcated in males, prosternal process deflexed behind coxae, rarely with small projecting tubercle near apex; flight wings fully developed, meso- and metacoxae separated by more than mesocoxal width; femora lacking smooth rounded callosities; outer margins of tibia flat with two indistinct rows of callosities, apical spine absent on all tibia in males, all male femora with rounded protuberance on anterior edge of basal half.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
